The paper deals with algorithms for maintaining and using the dominator tree of a directed graph, which is a fundamental data structure in graph theory and has applications in various areas such as program optimization, circuit testing, and biology. The paper also introduces the concept of low-high orders, which are preorders of the dominator tree that have further applications in connectivity and path-determination problems. Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), cs.CG (Computational Geometry), and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics). The paper also presents an application of low-high orders to the smallest 2-vertex-connected spanning subgraph problem (2VCSS), which involves finding a subgraph that connects all vertices of a graph and has no cut vertices. This suggests that the paper could also be relevant to cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.NA (Numerical Analysis), which are sub-categories that often deal with optimization problems and graph algorithms.
